{
  "local_port": 37002,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I distinguish between different ranks of the Indian army?",
  "response": "The Indian Army's rank structure is hierarchical and can be distinguished by titles and insignia. Here's a structured breakdown:\n\n### **Commissioned Officers (Descending Order)**\n1. **Field Marshal** (Honorary): \n   - **Insignia**: National emblem over crossed batons in a wreath.\n2. **General**: \n   - **Insignia**: Crossed baton and sword with four stars.\n3. **Lieutenant General**: \n   - **Insignia**: Crossed baton and sword with three stars.\n4. **Major General**: \n   - **Insignia**: Crossed baton and sword with two stars.\n5. **Brigadier**: \n   - **Insignia**: Three stars (without crossed symbols).\n6. **Colonel**: \n   - **Insignia**: Two stars.\n7. **Lieutenant Colonel**: \n   - **Insignia**: One star.\n8. **Major**: \n   - **Insignia**: Ashoka emblem (lion capital).\n9. **Captain**: \n   - **Insignia**: Three vertical stars.\n10. **Lieutenant**: \n    - **Insignia**: Two vertical stars.\n\n### **Junior Commissioned Officers (JCOs)**\n1. **Subedar Major**: \n   - **Insignia**: Five stripes with a national emblem.\n2. **Subedar**: \n   - **Insignia**: Three stripes with a star.\n3. **Naib Subedar**: \n   - **Insignia**: Two stripes with a star.\n\n### **Non-Commissioned Officers (NCOs) and Other Ranks**\n1. **Havildar**: \n   - **Insignia**: Three chevrons.\n2. **Naik**: \n   - **Insignia**: Two chevrons.\n3. **Lance Naik**: \n   - **Insignia**: One chevron.\n4. **Sepoy**: \n   - **Insignia**: No insignia (entry-level rank).\n\n### **Key Notes**\n- **Hierarchy**: Commissioned Officers > JCOs > NCOs > Sepoys.\n- **Insignia Features**:\n  - **General Officers** (Brigadier and above): Stars with or without crossed baton/sword.\n  - **Senior/Junior Officers**: Stars or Ashoka emblem.\n  - **JCOs**: Stripes and stars.\n  - **NCOs**: Chevrons.\n\nThis structure helps in identifying ranks through titles and visual symbols, ensuring clear distinction within the Indian Army's disciplined framework.",
